<subSubSection id="C361428CFFE5FFD6ABDE6E2452E0FA23" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="377" pageId="7" pageNumber="376" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BC41107FFE5FFD9ABDE6E24511CFDA6" blockId="7.[677,1210,573,968]" box="[677,821,573,599]" pageId="7" pageNumber="376">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC41107FFE5FFD9ABDE6E445623FC3B" blockId="7.[677,1210,573,968]" pageId="7" pageNumber="376">
The sponge is erect and forms numerous cylindrical branches (
<quantity id="4C83BCE2FFE5FFD9AA236E62518CFD67" box="[856,933,634,661]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="376" unit="cm" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1-2 cm</quantity>
in diameter), which arise from a common base and divide dichotomically (
<figureCitation id="13400D82FFE5FFD9ABD76EA05128FD20" box="[684,769,697,723]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="8.[114,125,1190,1207]" captionTargetBox="[112,1210,203,1160]" captionTargetId="figure-4@8.[99,1230,190,1176]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIG. 6. — Microxina lanceolata n. sp.; A, paratype; B, C, ectosomal oxeas which form tufts supporting the pore sieve membrane (arrow); D, areolate surface showing the inhalant sieves supported by the oxeas; E, oscule; F, choanosomal skeleton; G, lanceolate extremity of an oxea; H, sigma. Scale bars: A, 1 cm; B, 50 µm; C, 20 µm; D, E, 1.5 mm; F, 400 µm; G, H, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757727" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757727/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="376">Fig. 6A</figureCitation>
). Some specimens may attain a height of 
<quantity id="4C83BCE2FFE5FFD9ABDE6ECE5127FD03" box="[677,782,726,753]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="376" unit="cm" value="35.0" valueMax="40.0" valueMin="30.0">30-40 cm</quantity>
and look bushy. The colour of alcoholpreserved specimens is pale yellow, beige, grey or brown. The consistency is soft and fragile. The surface is areolate; most areolae bear pore sieves and some oscules; both are supported by an erect series of oxeas forming a rim (
<figureCitation id="13400D82FFE5FFD9AA896F685645FC79" box="[1010,1132,880,907]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="8.[114,125,1190,1207]" captionTargetBox="[112,1210,203,1160]" captionTargetId="figure-4@8.[99,1230,190,1176]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIG. 6. — Microxina lanceolata n. sp.; A, paratype; B, C, ectosomal oxeas which form tufts supporting the pore sieve membrane (arrow); D, areolate surface showing the inhalant sieves supported by the oxeas; E, oscule; F, choanosomal skeleton; G, lanceolate extremity of an oxea; H, sigma. Scale bars: A, 1 cm; B, 50 µm; C, 20 µm; D, E, 1.5 mm; F, 400 µm; G, H, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757727" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757727/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="376">Fig. 6D, E</figureCitation>
). Only well-preserved specimens retain this ectosomal specialization which is easily lost.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC41107FFE5FFD9ABDE6FF250D3FBF6" blockId="7.[677,1210,1003,1520]" box="[677,762,1003,1029]" pageId="7" pageNumber="376">
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFE5FFD9ABDE6FF250D3FBF6" box="[677,762,1003,1029]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="376">Skeleton</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC41107FFE5FFD9ABDE681351A9FB6C" blockId="7.[677,1210,1003,1520]" pageId="7" pageNumber="376">
The ectosome includes perpendicular tufts of oxea surrounding the areolae and is supported by extensions of the choanosomal spicule tracts (
<figureCitation id="13400D82FFE5FFD9ABD7687F510CFB73" box="[684,805,1126,1152]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="8.[114,125,1190,1207]" captionTargetBox="[112,1210,203,1160]" captionTargetId="figure-4@8.[99,1230,190,1176]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIG. 6. — Microxina lanceolata n. sp.; A, paratype; B, C, ectosomal oxeas which form tufts supporting the pore sieve membrane (arrow); D, areolate surface showing the inhalant sieves supported by the oxeas; E, oscule; F, choanosomal skeleton; G, lanceolate extremity of an oxea; H, sigma. Scale bars: A, 1 cm; B, 50 µm; C, 20 µm; D, E, 1.5 mm; F, 400 µm; G, H, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757727" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757727/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="376">Fig. 6B, C</figureCitation>
). Tangential spicules are absent even between the areolae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC41107FFE5FFD9ABDE68BA511AFA03" blockId="7.[677,1210,1003,1520]" pageId="7" pageNumber="376">
The rather loose choanosomal skeleton is made up by ascending paucispicular (three to eight) tracts (50-180 µm thick) which are parallel or slightly plumose and connected by transverse spicules (two to three) (
<figureCitation id="13400D82FFE5FFD9AABB69075633FACB" box="[960,1050,1310,1336]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="8.[114,125,1190,1207]" captionTargetBox="[112,1210,203,1160]" captionTargetId="figure-4@8.[99,1230,190,1176]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIG. 6. — Microxina lanceolata n. sp.; A, paratype; B, C, ectosomal oxeas which form tufts supporting the pore sieve membrane (arrow); D, areolate surface showing the inhalant sieves supported by the oxeas; E, oscule; F, choanosomal skeleton; G, lanceolate extremity of an oxea; H, sigma. Scale bars: A, 1 cm; B, 50 µm; C, 20 µm; D, E, 1.5 mm; F, 400 µm; G, H, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757727" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757727/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="376">Fig. 6F</figureCitation>
). The spicule tracts diverge towards the sponge surface and merge with the ectosomal oxea layer. Interstitial spicules and dispersed microscleres (sigmas) are rare. Several yellow-brown embryos with a diameter of about 200 µm are incubated within the choanosome.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC41107FFE5FFD9ABDE6A0A50DCF9DE" blockId="7.[677,1210,1555,1704]" box="[677,757,1555,1581]" pageId="7" pageNumber="376">
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFE5FFD9ABDE6A0A50DCF9DE" box="[677,757,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="376">Spicules</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC41107FFE5FFD6ABDE6A2B504DFA86" blockId="7.[677,1210,1555,1704]" lastBlockId="8.[114,647,1309,1489]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="377" pageId="7" pageNumber="376">
Oxeas are mostly straight or seldom slightly curved (
<figureCitation id="13400D82FFE5FFD9AB856A48517DF998" box="[766,852,1617,1643]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="9.[148,159,741,758]" captionTargetBox="[277,1150,204,715]" captionTargetId="figure-442@9.[243,1150,186,730]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIG. 7. — Microxina lanceolata n. sp.; A, straight oxeas; B, sigmas; C, oxea extremities. Scale bars: A, 100 µm; B, C, 50 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757729" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757729/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="376">Fig. 7A</figureCitation>
), their ends are generally acerate although abruptly bent tips and lanceolate extremities are common (
<figureCitation id="13400D82FFE5FFD9AAAB6A975618F95B" box="[976,1073,1678,1704]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="8.[114,125,1190,1207]" captionTargetBox="[112,1210,203,1160]" captionTargetId="figure-4@8.[99,1230,190,1176]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIG. 6. — Microxina lanceolata n. sp.; A, paratype; B, C, ectosomal oxeas which form tufts supporting the pore sieve membrane (arrow); D, areolate surface showing the inhalant sieves supported by the oxeas; E, oscule; F, choanosomal skeleton; G, lanceolate extremity of an oxea; H, sigma. Scale bars: A, 1 cm; B, 50 µm; C, 20 µm; D, E, 1.5 mm; F, 400 µm; G, H, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757727" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757727/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="376">Figs 6G</figureCitation>
; 
<figureCitation id="13400D82FFE5FFD9AD3B6A97564EF95B" box="[1088,1127,1678,1704]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="9.[148,159,741,758]" captionTargetBox="[277,1150,204,715]" captionTargetId="figure-442@9.[243,1150,186,730]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIG. 7. — Microxina lanceolata n. sp.; A, straight oxeas; B, sigmas; C, oxea extremities. Scale bars: A, 100 µm; B, C, 50 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757729" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757729/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="376">7C</figureCitation>
). Oxea measure 390-525 (450) × 11-20 (16.3) µm. Straight, slender and much thinner oxeas (8 µm) are considered developmental stages (
<figureCitation id="13400D82FFEAFFD6AB7869425071FA86" box="[515,600,1371,1397]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="9.[148,159,741,758]" captionTargetBox="[277,1150,204,715]" captionTargetId="figure-442@9.[243,1150,186,730]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIG. 7. — Microxina lanceolata n. sp.; A, straight oxeas; B, sigmas; C, oxea extremities. Scale bars: A, 100 µm; B, C, 50 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757729" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757729/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">Fig. 7A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF04418FFFEAFFD6A90968BF563AFB12" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757727" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5757727" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757727/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="377" startId="8.[114,125,1190,1207]" targetBox="[112,1210,203,1160]" targetPageId="8">
<paragraph id="8BC41107FFEAFFD6A90968BF563AFB12" blockId="8.[114,1210,1190,1249]" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">
FIG. 6. — 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B6A84FFEAFFD6A9BD68BF535AFB44" authority="Calcinai &amp; Pansini, 2000" authorityName="Calcinai &amp; Pansini" authorityYear="2000" box="[198,371,1190,1207]" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="8" pageNumber="377" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="lanceolata" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEAFFD6A9BD68BF535AFB44" box="[198,371,1190,1207]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">Microxina lanceolata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A23C706EFFEAFFD6A80168BF5384FB44" box="[378,429,1190,1207]" pageId="8" pageNumber="377" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
; 
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEAFFD6A8CD68BF53EAFB44" bold="true" box="[438,451,1190,1207]" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">A</emphasis>
, paratype; 
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEAFFD6AB5F68BF5018FB44" bold="true" box="[548,561,1190,1207]" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">B</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEAFFD6AB4668BF5062FB44" bold="true" box="[573,587,1190,1207]" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">C</emphasis>
, ectosomal oxeas which form tufts supporting the pore sieve membrane (arrow); 
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEAFFD6A9CE68A252EAFB3F" bold="true" box="[181,195,1211,1228]" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">D</emphasis>
, areolate surface showing the inhalant sieves supported by the oxeas; 
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEAFFD6AA6C68A2510AFB3F" bold="true" box="[791,803,1211,1228]" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">E</emphasis>
, oscule; 
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEAFFD6AA1468A25153FB3F" bold="true" box="[879,890,1211,1228]" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">F</emphasis>
, choanosomal skeleton; 
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEAFFD6AD3068A25670FB3F" bold="true" box="[1099,1113,1211,1228]" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">G</emphasis>
, lanceolate extremity of an oxea; 
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEAFFD6A85D68C9531DFB12" bold="true" box="[294,308,1232,1249]" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">H</emphasis>
, sigma. Scale bars: A, 1 cm; B, 50 µm; C, 20 µm; D, E, 1.5 mm; F, 400 µm; G, H, 10 µm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BC41107FFEAFFD6A909696352E0FA23" blockId="8.[114,647,1309,1489]" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">
Sigmas are always present but not abundant (
<figureCitation id="13400D82FFEAFFD6A902698052F7FA40" box="[121,222,1433,1459]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="8.[114,125,1190,1207]" captionTargetBox="[112,1210,203,1160]" captionTargetId="figure-4@8.[99,1230,190,1176]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIG. 6. — Microxina lanceolata n. sp.; A, paratype; B, C, ectosomal oxeas which form tufts supporting the pore sieve membrane (arrow); D, areolate surface showing the inhalant sieves supported by the oxeas; E, oscule; F, choanosomal skeleton; G, lanceolate extremity of an oxea; H, sigma. Scale bars: A, 1 cm; B, 50 µm; C, 20 µm; D, E, 1.5 mm; F, 400 µm; G, H, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757727" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757727/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">Figs 6H</figureCitation>
; 
<figureCitation id="13400D82FFEAFFD6A9956981533BFA41" box="[238,274,1432,1458]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="9.[148,159,741,758]" captionTargetBox="[277,1150,204,715]" captionTargetId="figure-442@9.[243,1150,186,730]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIG. 7. — Microxina lanceolata n. sp.; A, straight oxeas; B, sigmas; C, oxea extremities. Scale bars: A, 100 µm; B, C, 50 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757729" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757729/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">7B</figureCitation>
); they measure 25-60 (42.6) × 2-4 µm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C361428CFFEAFFD7A90969ED56BBFB8C" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="378" pageId="8" pageNumber="377" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BC41107FFEAFFD6A90969ED52FFF9FF" blockId="8.[114,647,1524,1704]" box="[114,214,1524,1550]" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC41107FFEAFFD6A9096A0A5690F95B" blockId="8.[114,647,1524,1704]" lastBlockId="8.[677,1210,1309,1704]" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">
A remarkable number of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B6A84FFEAFFD6A8F26A0A5037F9DE" authorityName="Topsent" authorityYear="1928" box="[393,542,1555,1581]" class="Demospongiae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="8" pageNumber="377" phylum="Porifera" rank="order">Haplosclerida</taxonomicName>
with sigmas and microxeas were recorded from continental Antarctic and 
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEAFFD6A8546A49535CF99A" box="[303,373,1616,1641]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">circum</emphasis>
Antarctic islands (Sarà 
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEAFFD6AB0E6A4952AFF97A" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">et al</emphasis>
. 1992) and attributed to the genera 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B6A84FFEAFFD6AB486A7652F6F95B" authority=", Haliclona" authorityName="Haliclona" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Gellius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="8" pageNumber="377" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEAFFD6AB486A7652F6F95B" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">Gellius, Haliclona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEAFFD6A8676A9453BEF955" box="[284,407,1677,1702]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">
<taxonomicName id="4C7B6A84FFEAFFD6A8676A9453BAF955" authorityName="Topsent" authorityYear="1916" box="[284,403,1677,1702]" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="8" pageNumber="377" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">Microxina</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
However, as Boury- Esnault &amp; Van Beveren (1982) pointed out, there is confusion in the taxonomy of this group and a worldwide revision is needed. Boury-Esnault &amp; Van Beveren (1982) decided to use the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B6A84FFEAFFD6ABDE698050DDFA40" box="[677,756,1433,1459]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Gellius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="8" pageNumber="377" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEAFFD6ABDE698050DDFA40" box="[677,756,1433,1459]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">Gellius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in a broad sense in their study of the demosponges of the Kerguelen and 
<collectingCountry id="F36C5197FFEAFFD6AD1569AE5693FA22" box="[1134,1210,1463,1489]" name="Heard Island and McDonald Islands" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">Heard</collectingCountry>
Islands. More recently, Wiedenmayer (1989: 105) synonymized 
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEAFFD6AAF269EC5627F9FC" box="[905,1038,1525,1551]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">Hemigellius</emphasis>
Burton, 1932 with 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B6A84FFEAFFD6AB9B6A0A51D5F9DE" authority="Topsent, 1916" authorityName="Topsent" authorityYear="1916" box="[736,1020,1554,1581]" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="8" pageNumber="377" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEAFFD6AB9B6A0A5167F9DF" box="[736,846,1555,1580]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">Microxina</emphasis>
Topsent, 1916
</taxonomicName>
, two genera that are nearly identical except for the microscleres, sigmas in the former and microxeas in the latter (see Van Soest 1980: 109). This decision seems justified because 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B6A84FFEAFFD6AA126A945606F95B" box="[873,1071,1677,1704]" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="8" pageNumber="377" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEAFFD6AA126A9451F3F955" box="[873,986,1677,1702]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="377">Microxina</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
which have
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC41107FFEBFFD7A9A66CD752C7FF14" blockId="9.[221,238,206,231]" box="[221,238,206,231]" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">A</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC41107FFEBFFD7A9A66DF752C6FDF4" blockId="9.[221,239,494,519]" box="[221,239,494,519]" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">B</paragraph>
<caption id="DF04418FFFEBFFD7A9EF6EFC56B1FD05" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757729" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5757729" box="[148,1176,741,758]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757729/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="378" startId="9.[148,159,741,758]" targetBox="[277,1150,204,715]" targetPageId="9">
<paragraph id="8BC41107FFEBFFD7A9EF6EFC56B1FD05" blockId="9.[148,1176,741,758]" box="[148,1176,741,758]" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">
FIG. 7. — 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B6A84FFEBFFD7A99F6EFC53A7FD05" authority="Calcinai &amp; Pansini, 2000" authorityName="Calcinai &amp; Pansini" authorityYear="2000" box="[228,398,741,758]" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="378" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="lanceolata" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEBFFD7A99F6EFC53A7FD05" box="[228,398,741,758]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">Microxina lanceolata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A23C706EFFEBFFD7A8EF6EFC53EFFD05" box="[404,454,741,758]" pageId="9" pageNumber="378" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
; 
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEBFFD7A8B76EFC53F0FD05" bold="true" box="[460,473,741,758]" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">A</emphasis>
, straight oxeas; 
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEBFFD7AB186EFC5059FD05" bold="true" box="[611,624,741,758]" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">B</emphasis>
, sigmas; 
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEBFFD7ABBA6EFC50E6FD05" bold="true" box="[705,719,741,758]" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">C</emphasis>
, oxea extremities. Scale bars: A, 100 µm; B, C, 50 µm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BC41107FFEBFFD7A90A6F2A5020FAEB" blockId="9.[113,647,818,1704]" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">
both sigmas and microxeas as microscleres actually exist (e.g. 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B6A84FFEBFFD7A86A6F4850ABFC9F" authority="(Topsent, 1901))" authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Topsent" baseAuthorityYear="1901" box="[273,642,849,876]" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="378" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="benedeni">
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEBFFD7A86A6F48538AFC9F" box="[273,419,849,876]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">M. benedeni</emphasis>
(Topsent, 1901))
</taxonomicName>
. Wiedenmayer (1989) stated that “toxa also occur in some species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B6A84FFEBFFD7A82A6F9653FAFC5A" authorityName="Van Soest" authorityYear="1980" box="[337,467,911,937]" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="378" phylum="Porifera" rank="family">Niphatidae</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEBFFD7A89C6F97504CFC5B" box="[487,613,910,936]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">
<taxonomicName id="4C7B6A84FFEBFFD7A89C6F975074FC5B" authorityName="Topsent" authorityYear="1916" box="[487,605,910,936]" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="378" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">Microxina</taxonomicName>
)
</emphasis>
of which 
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEBFFD7A9C06FB7531CFC3B" box="[187,309,942,968]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">Hemigellius</emphasis>
is here considered a synonym” emending 
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEBFFD7A9966FD4536AFC16" box="[237,323,971,999]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">de facto</emphasis>
the definition of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B6A84FFEBFFD7A90A6FF252C8FBF7" authorityName="Topsent" authorityYear="1916" box="[113,225,1003,1028]" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="378" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEBFFD7A90A6FF252C8FBF7" box="[113,225,1003,1028]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">Microxina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to receive also species bearing toxas. This allowed Hooper &amp; Wiedenmayer (1994) to attribute to 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B6A84FFEBFFD7A863683153BCFBB2" authorityName="Topsent" authorityYear="1916" box="[280,405,1064,1089]" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="378" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEBFFD7A863683153BCFBB2" box="[280,405,1064,1089]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">Microxina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
several species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B6A84FFEBFFD7A90A685E532FFB92" authorityName="Topsent" authorityYear="1928" box="[113,262,1095,1121]" class="Demospongiae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="378" phylum="Porifera" rank="order">Haplosclerida</taxonomicName>
with toxas, such as 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B6A84FFEBFFD7A898685E5364FB73" authority="(Kirkpatrick, 1907)" baseAuthorityName="Kirkpatrick" baseAuthorityYear="1907" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="378" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="phakelloides">
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEBFFD7A898685E50AEFB92" box="[483,647,1095,1121]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">M. phakelloides</emphasis>
(Kirkpatrick, 1907)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B6A84FFEBFFD7A8F2687C5292FB6C" authority="(Topsent, 1916)" baseAuthorityName="Topsent" baseAuthorityYear="1916" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="378" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="spongiosa">
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEBFFD7A8F2687C503DFB8D" box="[393,532,1125,1150]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">M. spongiosa</emphasis>
(Topsent, 1916)
</taxonomicName>
, and “ 
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEBFFD7A877689D502AFB6C" box="[268,515,1156,1183]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">
<taxonomicName id="4C7B6A84FFEBFFD7A877689D53AAFB6D" authorityName="Topsent" authorityYear="1916" box="[268,387,1156,1182]" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="378" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">Microxina</taxonomicName>
” flagellifer
</emphasis>
(Ridley &amp; Dendy, 1886). We agree with the proposed synonymy but, for the moment, will restrict its use to species that being devoid of toxas would have previously been placed in 
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEBFFD7A8F268E6502AFAEA" box="[393,515,1279,1305]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">Hemigellius</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC41107FFEBFFD7A90A69075316FA22" blockId="9.[113,647,818,1704]" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">
The new species is attributed to 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B6A84FFEBFFD7A89569045049FAC5" authorityName="Topsent" authorityYear="1916" box="[494,608,1309,1334]" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="378" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEBFFD7A89569045049FAC5" box="[494,608,1309,1334]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">Microxina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on account of its skeletal structure. It is well separated from other species by its shape, spear-shaped oxea extremities, peculiar cribrose appearance of its surface, and absence of tangentially arranged ectosomal spicules.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC41107FFEBFFD7A90A69CF56BBFB8C" blockId="9.[113,647,818,1704]" lastBlockId="9.[677,1210,818,1152]" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">
Based on the skeleton structure, the closest species is 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B6A84FFEBFFD7A99B69ED532FF9DE" authority="Burton, 1932" authorityName="Burton" authorityYear="1932" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="378" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="pachydermata" subGenus="Hemigellius">
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEBFFD7A99B69ED50AFF9FC" box="[224,646,1524,1551]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">Microxina (Hemigellius) pachydermata</emphasis>
Burton, 1932
</taxonomicName>
which too has a dermal palisade of oxeas but differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B6A84FFEBFFD7A80A6A28502DF9BF" authorityName="Calcinai &amp; Pansini" authorityYear="2000" box="[369,516,1585,1612]" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="378" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="lanceolata">
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEBFFD7A80A6A2853A0F9B9" box="[369,393,1585,1610]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEBFFD7A8E16A2B502DF9BF" box="[410,516,1586,1612]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">lanceolata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its even surface (with regularly distributed pores), by shape and size of oxeas, and by absence of sigmas. 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B6A84FFEBFFD7A90A6A945029F95B" authority="sensu Topsent, 1901" authorityName="sensu Topsent" authorityYear="1901" box="[113,512,1677,1704]" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="378" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="rudis">
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEBFFD7A90A6A945371F955" box="[113,344,1677,1704]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">Microxina rudis sensu</emphasis>
Topsent, 1901
</taxonomicName>
(see Boury- Esnault &amp; Van Beveren 1982: 117 regarding the genotype of 
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEBFFD7AA4D6F4B519EFC9F" box="[822,951,850,876]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">Hemigellius</emphasis>
) differs from the new species by its massive shape, by having thin, often centrotylote sigmas, and by an ectosomal reticulation of tangentially arranged oxeas. Finally, 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B6A84FFEBFFD7ABDE6FD550CFFBF6" authority="(Kirkpatrick, 1907)" baseAuthorityName="Kirkpatrick" baseAuthorityYear="1907" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="378" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="pilosa" subGenus="Hemigellius">
<emphasis id="B90FCD15FFEBFFD7ABDE6FD55638FC14" box="[677,1041,972,999]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="378">Microxina (Hemigellius) pilosa</emphasis>
(Kirkpatrick, 1907)
</taxonomicName>
is erect and ramified like 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B6A84FFEBFFD7AA846FF256A7FBF6" authorityName="Calcinai &amp; Pansini" authorityYear="2000" box="[1023,1166,1002,1029]" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="378" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="lanceolata">
